SIMPLE: persian
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Persian
<hw>Per"sian</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From
<ets>Persia</ets>: cf. It. <ets>Persiano</ets>. Cf. <er>Parsee</er>,
<er>Peach</er>, <er>Persic</er>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to Persia,
to the Persians, or to their language.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Persian berry</b></col>, <cd>the fruit of <spn>Rhamnus
infectorius</spn>, a kind of buckthorn, used for dyeing yellow, and
imported chiefly from Trebizond.</cd> -- <col><b>Persian cat</b></col>.
<fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>Same as <spn>Angora cat</spn>, under
<er>Angora</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Persian columns</b></col>
<fld>(Arch.)</fld>, <cd>columns of which the shaft represents a Persian
slave; -- called also <altname>Persians</altname>. See
<er>Atlantes</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Persian drill</b></col>
<fld>(Mech.)</fld>, <cd>a drill which is turned by pushing a nut back
and forth along a spirally grooved drill holder.</cd> -- <col><b>Persian
fire</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>malignant pustule.</cd> --
<col><b>Persian powder</b></col>. <cd>See <cref>Insect powder</cref>,
under <er>Insect</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Persian red</b></col>. <cd>See
<cref>Indian red</cref> <sd>(a)</sd>, under <er>Indian</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Persian wheel</b></col>, <cd>a noria; a tympanum. See
<er>Noria</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Persian</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Persian
<hw>Per"sian</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A native or inhabitant
of Persia.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The language spoken in Persia. Ancient Persian of
the 3rd to 10th centuries is also called <stype>Pahlavi</stype>, and
modern Persian is also called <stype>Farsi</stype>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A thin silk fabric, used formerly for linings.</def>
<rj><au>Beck.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>See
<cref>Persian columns</cref>, under <er>Persian</er>,
<pos>a.</pos></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Persic</ent>⟦br⟧
